I want to look at

29
00:00:43,086 --> 00:00:45,336
key aspects of
the smart state.

30
00:00:45,536 --> 00:00:46,373
And I'll conclude

31
00:00:46,536 --> 00:00:47,473
by looking at some

32
00:00:47,673 --> 00:00:48,598
good examples

33
00:00:48,798 --> 00:00:50,348
from regions
around Europe.

34
00:00:51,111 --> 00:00:53,211
smart specialisation policy

35
00:00:54,123 --> 00:00:55,273
is the most ambitious

36
00:00:55,423 --> 00:00:56,923
regional innovation policy

37
00:00:57,048 --> 00:00:57,873
ever introduced

38
00:00:58,023 --> 00:00:59,211
anywhere in the world.

39
00:01:00,136 --> 00:01:00,811
But it makes

40
00:01:00,923 --> 00:01:03,311
two major presumptions

41
00:01:03,511 --> 00:01:04,511
which are not often

42
00:01:04,711 --> 00:01:05,723
explicitly made.

43
00:01:07,036 --> 00:01:08,561
The first presumption

44
00:01:09,023 --> 00:01:10,886
is a political presumption.

45
00:01:10,885 --> 00:01:12,336
And it presumes that

46
00:01:12,398 --> 00:01:13,886
regional elites

47
00:01:13,923 --> 00:01:15,573
really want to innovate.

48
00:01:16,198 --> 00:01:17,373
But in actual fact

49
00:01:17,410 --> 00:01:18,311
they may simply

50
00:01:18,360 --> 00:01:20,011
want to retain control

51
00:01:20,060 --> 00:01:21,723
or simply maintain

52
00:01:21,760 --> 00:01:22,898
the status quo.

53
00:01:23,723 --> 00:01:25,386
The second major presumption:

54
00:01:25,798 --> 00:01:27,211
Is that the state

55
00:01:27,673 --> 00:01:29,673
and its public sector agencies

56
00:01:29,822 --> 00:01:31,098
are really competent

57
00:01:31,260 --> 00:01:32,922
to meet the challenge

58
00:01:33,110 --> 00:01:34,535
of smart specialisation.

59
00:01:34,735 --> 00:01:36,772
Both these presumptions

60
00:01:36,972 --> 00:01:37,960
really need

61
00:01:38,160 --> 00:01:39,210
to be scrutinized

62
00:01:39,360 --> 00:01:40,660
very, very carefully.

63
00:01:41,722 --> 00:01:43,047
My first theme is about

64
00:01:43,247 --> 00:01:44,560
debates on the state

65
00:01:45,547 --> 00:01:46,060
And

66
00:01:46,260 --> 00:01:48,435
there's a certain state discourse

67
00:01:48,885 --> 00:01:50,635
about the role of the state

68
00:01:50,672 --> 00:01:52,085
in economic development.

69
00:01:52,847 --> 00:01:54,610
It is almost impossible

70
00:01:54,684 --> 00:01:56,747
- as Will Hutton shows here -

71
00:01:56,796 --> 00:01:58,160
"It's almost impossible

72
00:01:58,272 --> 00:02:00,010
to think straight about the state

73
00:02:00,059 --> 00:02:01,522
without assuming that

74
00:02:01,572 --> 00:02:02,822
we have to shrink it,

75
00:02:02,859 --> 00:02:03,997
fragment it,

76
00:02:04,046 --> 00:02:05,485
or privatise it."

77
00:02:05,947 --> 00:02:07,222
And this discourse

78
00:02:07,259 --> 00:02:09,185
is especially prominent

79
00:02:09,235 --> 00:02:10,772
in certain countries,

80
00:02:10,822 --> 00:02:12,997
like the United States of America

81
00:02:13,059 --> 00:02:14,360
or the United Kingdom,

82
00:02:14,422 --> 00:02:15,285
for example.

83
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:17,710
But it is true in varying degrees

84
00:02:17,760 --> 00:02:19,722
in many countries

85
00:02:19,922 --> 00:02:21,097
around the world.

86
00:02:21,297 --> 00:02:22,959
And we need to challenge

87
00:02:23,034 --> 00:02:25,060
this state discourse.

88
00:02:25,260 --> 00:02:26,647
Where does it come from?

89
00:02:26,847 --> 00:02:28,897
I think the state discourse

90
00:02:29,097 --> 00:02:30,622
was just critical of the state.

91
00:02:30,822 --> 00:02:32,172
It takes a very negative

92
00:02:32,322 --> 00:02:33,510
view of the state,

93
00:02:34,072 --> 00:02:35,535
really stems

94
00:02:35,735 --> 00:02:36,922
from the dominance

95
00:02:37,122 --> 00:02:38,335
of neoliberal ideology.

96
00:02:38,535 --> 00:02:41,535
And while some of that ideology

97
00:02:41,735 --> 00:02:42,922
is very crude,

98
00:02:43,472 --> 00:02:44,360
for example,

99
00:02:44,722 --> 00:02:45,747
less State

100
00:02:45,947 --> 00:02:47,298
equals more market,

101
00:02:47,498 --> 00:02:48,335
for example.

102
00:02:48,535 --> 00:02:49,397
That's very crude.

103
00:02:49,597 --> 00:02:51,722
I think there is a very serious

104
00:02:51,922 --> 00:02:53,947
philosophy behind some

105
00:02:54,147 --> 00:02:56,260
of the neoliberal criticisms

106
00:02:56,460 --> 00:02:57,422
of the state.

107
00:02:57,622 --> 00:02:59,635
And these...theories

108
00:02:59,810 --> 00:03:01,060
these critical theories

109
00:03:01,385 --> 00:03:02,548
stem originally from

110
00:03:02,760 --> 00:03:04,173
the work of Friedrich Hayek,

111
00:03:04,373 --> 00:03:06,323
who was a very, very serious

112
00:03:06,523 --> 00:03:08,285
...and sophisticated...

113
00:03:08,485 --> 00:03:10,235
...economic theorist.

114
00:03:10,660 --> 00:03:12,610
And these insights from Hayek's

115
00:03:12,810 --> 00:03:13,835
that are used today

116
00:03:14,073 --> 00:03:16,085
by neo-liberal critics of the State,

117
00:03:16,285 --> 00:03:18,385
boiled down to two things.

118
00:03:18,585 --> 00:03:19,573
First of all,

119
00:03:19,773 --> 00:03:20,973
they maintain

120
00:03:21,173 --> 00:03:23,048
that industrial policy

121
00:03:23,248 --> 00:03:24,635
should largely by avoided.

122
00:03:24,760 --> 00:03:25,747
Why?

123
00:03:25,873 --> 00:03:27,760
Because industrial policy...

124
00:03:27,960 --> 00:03:29,223
...encourages firms

125
00:03:29,423 --> 00:03:31,348
to engage in rent seeking.

126
00:03:31,548 --> 00:03:32,798
Or to seek

127
00:03:32,998 --> 00:03:35,035
special privileges from the state.

128
00:03:35,235 --> 00:03:36,898
For example, state subsidies.

129
00:03:37,148 --> 00:03:39,348
When they should be seeking
to innovate.

130
00:03:39,585 --> 00:03:41,735
Rather than to engage
in rent seeking.

131
00:03:41,798 --> 00:03:43,473
And therefore
industrial policy

132
00:03:43,560 --> 00:03:44,773
should be avoided

133
00:03:45,035 --> 00:03:46,973
and picking winners
should be avoided

134
00:03:47,148 --> 00:03:48,373
Because the state

135
00:03:48,523 --> 00:03:50,273
creates perverse incentives

136
00:03:50,448 --> 00:03:51,423
for firms.

137
00:03:51,885 --> 00:03:54,510
And the second...criticism

138
00:03:54,710 --> 00:03:57,198
that stems from Hayek's work,
I think,

139
00:03:57,398 --> 00:04:00,648
is about the informational
capacity of the state.

140
00:04:00,798 --> 00:04:03,198
The State can never be
a surrogate,

141
00:04:03,398 --> 00:04:05,498
can never be a substitute,
in other words

142
00:04:05,698 --> 00:04:07,085
for the decentralized

143
00:04:07,285 --> 00:04:09,798
information processing capacity

144
00:04:09,960 --> 00:04:10,698
of markets.

145
00:04:10,898 --> 00:04:12,473
And therefore,

146
00:04:12,673 --> 00:04:14,698
these two assumptions together

147
00:04:14,898 --> 00:04:16,285
have boiled down

148
00:04:16,485 --> 00:04:17,760
to a neoliberal critique

149
00:04:17,960 --> 00:04:18,685
of the State

150
00:04:18,885 --> 00:04:22,459
which often suggests
to policy makers

151
00:04:22,885 --> 00:04:25,585
that the public sector is bad.

152
00:04:25,785 --> 00:04:28,335
While the private sector is good.

153
00:04:28,535 --> 00:04:30,535
And we need to get beyond

154
00:04:30,735 --> 00:04:33,735
that simple binary antithesis.

155
00:04:34,560 --> 00:04:35,948
In recent years,

156
00:04:36,148 --> 00:04:37,973
there has been a number

157
00:04:38,173 --> 00:04:40,135
...of interesting...critiques

158
00:04:40,335 --> 00:04:42,448
of this neoliberal criticism.

159
00:04:43,673 --> 00:04:45,298
A very interesting one

160
00:04:45,360 --> 00:04:47,435
comes from Mariana Mazzucato

161
00:04:47,523 --> 00:04:49,548
who wrote a very stimulating book

162
00:04:49,710 --> 00:04:51,623
called "The Entrepreneurial State".

163
00:04:52,085 --> 00:04:53,210
In this book,

164
00:04:53,273 --> 00:04:55,123
Mazzucato tries to change

165
00:04:55,248 --> 00:04:56,735
the way we think

166
00:04:56,835 --> 00:04:58,760
and talk about the state.

167
00:04:58,835 --> 00:05:00,748
To try to paint the state

168
00:05:00,785 --> 00:05:02,185
in a positive light

169
00:05:02,310 --> 00:05:04,710
rather than a purely negative light.

170
00:05:04,973 --> 00:05:06,448
She shows that the state

171
00:05:06,535 --> 00:05:07,973
can be innovative

172
00:05:08,073 --> 00:05:09,248
and risk-taking.

173
00:05:09,323 --> 00:05:11,448
And to prove her argument

174
00:05:11,523 --> 00:05:12,898
she takes the example

175
00:05:12,948 --> 00:05:14,460
of Apple's technologies.

176
00:05:14,498 --> 00:05:15,935
And she shows how

177
00:05:15,985 --> 00:05:17,223
all these technologies

178
00:05:17,310 --> 00:05:19,248
in the iPhone, for example,

179
00:05:19,285 --> 00:05:21,685
were all funded by the state

180
00:05:21,723 --> 00:05:23,660
through federal grants.

181
00:05:23,860 --> 00:05:26,860
This is a marvelously
stimulating book

182
00:05:27,060 --> 00:05:29,298
But if I had a criticism
to make of it

183
00:05:29,348 --> 00:05:31,285
it would be that she

184
00:05:31,298 --> 00:05:33,498
underplays the creativity of Apple

185
00:05:33,698 --> 00:05:35,860
Because any firm could have

186
00:05:35,898 --> 00:05:37,473
developed those projects,

187
00:05:37,560 --> 00:05:38,760
but only Apple did.

188
00:05:38,810 --> 00:05:41,310
And it overplays the creativity

189
00:05:41,348 --> 00:05:42,923
of the public sector.

190
00:05:43,123 --> 00:05:44,623
She looks at very unique

191
00:05:44,698 --> 00:05:46,485
public sector agencies,

192
00:05:46,548 --> 00:05:48,760
like Darper, from the United States,

193
00:05:48,785 --> 00:05:49,423
for example,

194
00:05:49,485 --> 00:05:50,348
which I think

195
00:05:50,410 --> 00:05:51,785
is the exception,

196
00:05:51,823 --> 00:05:53,610
rather than the norm

197
00:05:53,635 --> 00:05:55,885
of public sector agencies.

198
00:05:56,085 --> 00:05:58,048
What about other positions?

199
00:05:58,898 --> 00:06:00,460
The most important critique

200
00:06:00,498 --> 00:06:02,423
of the neoliberal position,

201
00:06:02,460 --> 00:06:03,585
in my view,

202
00:06:03,635 --> 00:06:04,623
is what I would call

203
00:06:04,673 --> 00:06:07,110
the experimentalist approach

204
00:06:07,185 --> 00:06:09,635
of people like Danny Rodrick

205
00:06:09,648 --> 00:06:11,193
and Charles Sabel.

206
00:06:12,118 --> 00:06:14,068
What Rodrick does, for example,

207
00:06:14,130 --> 00:06:16,868
he accepts the Hayek critique

208
00:06:16,930 --> 00:06:19,280
that the State lacks information.

209
00:06:19,905 --> 00:06:21,480
But he turns this criticism

210
00:06:21,530 --> 00:06:23,005
on its head by saying

211
00:06:23,005 --> 00:06:24,755
the private sector

212
00:06:24,755 --> 00:06:24,768
also lacks information.
the private sector

213
00:06:24,768 --> 00:06:26,743
also lacks information.

214
00:06:26,943 --> 00:06:28,618
Both the public sector

215
00:06:28,818 --> 00:06:30,155
and the private sector

216
00:06:30,355 --> 00:06:31,968
lack information

217
00:06:32,030 --> 00:06:33,280
when they are engaging

218
00:06:33,405 --> 00:06:36,517
in experimenting
for new technologies,

219
00:06:36,567 --> 00:06:37,780
for innovation.

220
00:06:37,868 --> 00:06:41,505
And the implication of this insight

221
00:06:41,705 --> 00:06:44,493
is that both firms and states

222
00:06:44,693 --> 00:06:46,068
need to collaborate,

223
00:06:46,268 --> 00:06:47,530
to learn together,

224
00:06:47,730 --> 00:06:49,368
in a trial and error process

225
00:06:49,568 --> 00:06:50,955
of experimentation.

226
00:06:51,155 --> 00:06:53,693
The main aim of this process

227
00:06:53,718 --> 00:06:54,830
of trial and error

228
00:06:55,030 --> 00:06:57,005
is to try to secure,

229
00:06:57,205 --> 00:06:58,830
or illicit information.

230
00:06:59,030 --> 00:06:59,918
In other words,

231
00:06:59,943 --> 00:07:01,480
to find joint solutions

232
00:07:01,680 --> 00:07:03,243
to common problems

233
00:07:03,355 --> 00:07:04,868
and to evaluate outcomes

234
00:07:04,918 --> 00:07:06,630
almost in real time.

235
00:07:07,318 --> 00:07:08,480
And this process

236
00:07:08,530 --> 00:07:09,593
is sometimes called

237
00:07:09,693 --> 00:07:11,418
diagnostic monitoring.

238
00:07:12,443 --> 00:07:15,429
This is the smart state thesis

239
00:07:15,430 --> 00:07:17,717
which is is adopted in this MOOC.

240
00:07:17,768 --> 00:07:18,993
And it is presumed

241
00:07:19,030 --> 00:07:22,655
in the smart specialisation strategy

242
00:07:22,717 --> 00:07:24,642
of the European Commission.

243
00:07:24,680 --> 00:07:27,330
The smart state presumption

244
00:07:27,380 --> 00:07:29,705
is based on, and is an example of,

245
00:07:29,705 --> 00:07:29,743
what is sometimes called
is based on, and is an example of,

246
00:07:29,743 --> 00:07:31,105
what is sometimes called

247
00:07:31,180 --> 00:07:32,730
experimentalist governance.

248
00:07:32,918 --> 00:07:34,968
Experimentalist governance

249
00:07:35,168 --> 00:07:37,743
simply means a recursive process

250
00:07:37,780 --> 00:07:40,893
of provisional goal-setting
and revision

251
00:07:40,943 --> 00:07:42,218
based on learning from

252
00:07:42,330 --> 00:07:44,755
the comparison of
alternative approaches.

253
00:07:44,830 --> 00:07:46,317
This the definition that is

254
00:07:46,380 --> 00:07:48,918
given to experimental governance

255
00:07:48,968 --> 00:07:50,729
by Charles Sabel

256
00:07:50,755 --> 00:07:52,317
and Johnathan Zeitlin.

257
00:07:52,355 --> 00:07:53,168
For example,

258
00:07:53,268 --> 00:07:54,193
at bottom,

259
00:07:54,305 --> 00:07:56,493
it involves joint goal-setting

260
00:07:56,693 --> 00:07:58,855
between central and local units

261
00:07:59,055 --> 00:08:00,530
where local units

262
00:08:00,730 --> 00:08:02,218
have the discretion

263
00:08:02,418 --> 00:08:03,293
to meet the goals

264
00:08:03,493 --> 00:08:05,905
of a particular project in question.

265
00:08:06,105 --> 00:08:07,668
And these projects,

266
00:08:07,868 --> 00:08:10,280
are subject to a continuous process

267
00:08:10,480 --> 00:08:12,118
of diagnostic monitoring.

268
00:08:12,418 --> 00:08:14,268
But this is the important point.

269
00:08:14,643 --> 00:08:16,368
The primary aim

270
00:08:16,568 --> 00:08:18,330
of diagnostic monitoring

271
00:08:18,530 --> 00:08:21,905
is to build problem-solving capacity,

272
00:08:22,105 --> 00:08:24,943
not to police compliance.

273
00:08:25,143 --> 00:08:26,068
In other words,

274
00:08:26,180 --> 00:08:27,443
diagnostic monitoring

275
00:08:27,505 --> 00:08:29,505
is a tool for learning

276
00:08:29,618 --> 00:08:30,680
not control.

277
00:08:31,343 --> 00:08:33,230
While experimentalist governance

278
00:08:33,430 --> 00:08:36,093
is a very compelling principle,

279
00:08:36,155 --> 00:08:37,968
it is very challenging

280
00:08:38,018 --> 00:08:39,405
to do in practice

281
00:08:39,605 --> 00:08:41,643
for a number of reasons.

282
00:08:41,843 --> 00:08:42,693
For example,

283
00:08:42,893 --> 00:08:46,293
it presumes strong feedback.

284
00:08:46,493 --> 00:08:48,443
In all evolutionary theories,

285
00:08:48,530 --> 00:08:49,480
feedback

286
00:08:49,593 --> 00:08:51,893
plays an absolutely crucial role.

287
00:08:52,093 --> 00:08:53,443
But in practice,

288
00:08:53,643 --> 00:08:57,518
feedback is stymied by many things.

289
00:08:57,980 --> 00:09:01,505
Good feedback is stymied by fear,

290
00:09:01,579 --> 00:09:04,155
by power, by hierarchy

291
00:09:04,204 --> 00:09:07,355
I often say to my master students,

292
00:09:07,429 --> 00:09:10,055
Good feedback is like gold dust,

293
00:09:10,104 --> 00:09:12,218
and just as difficult to get.

294
00:09:12,255 --> 00:09:14,180
So we should never assume

295
00:09:14,229 --> 00:09:16,780
that feedback is readily available.

296
00:09:16,829 --> 00:09:18,217
Another barrier,

297
00:09:18,267 --> 00:09:20,529
is the public sector culture

298
00:09:20,579 --> 00:09:22,967
around failure.

299
00:09:23,679 --> 00:09:25,942
Failure is not tolerated

300
